\title{Spectral Gap Analysis for Efficient Tunneling in Quantum Adiabatic Optimization}

\author{Lucas~T.~Brady}
\affiliation{{Department of Physics, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106-5110, USA}}
\author{Wim~van~Dam}
\affiliation{{Department of Computer Science, Department of Physics, University of California, Santa Barbara, CA 93106-5110, USA}}





\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
We investigate Quantum Adiabatic Optimization of $n$ qubit systems where the
ground state must tunnel through a potential barrier during the annealing
process and where the configurations are weighted by a symmetric cost function
that has a potential barrier of width $n^\alpha$ and height $n^\beta$. The
optimization algorithm must tunnel through this barrier, and the time sufficient
to ensure tunneling grows quadratically with the inverse spectral gap during
this tunneling process. We analyze barrier sizes with $\alpha+\beta\geq 1/2$ and
$2\alpha+\beta<1$ and show that for these barriers the minimum gap scales
polynomially as $n^{1/2-\alpha-\beta}$. Our proof of this scaling uses
elementary techniques and confirms a portion of an unpublished folklore result
by Goldstone, which used large spin and instanton methods. 
\end{abstract}




\maketitle




\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Quantum Annealing ({\textsc{qa}\xspace}) seeks to solve optimization problems by taking a state of a quantum system and evolving its Hamiltonian to get a desired result.  Quantum Adiabatic Optimization ({\textsc{qao}\xspace}) \cite{Farhi2000} is a form of {\textsc{qa}\xspace} that seeks to keep a system in the ground state while adiabatically evolving the Hamiltonian.  A lot of recent work has gone into analyzing {\textsc{qao}\xspace} in its own right \cite{Farhi2002, Reichardt, Farhi2008} and comparing {\textsc{qao}\xspace} with classical algorithms such as Simulated Quantum Annealing via path-integral Quantum Monte Carlo \cite{Heim,Boxio2,Martonak,Hastings,Muthukrishnan,Brady,Crosson} to see how much speed-up {\textsc{qao}\xspace} can give if any. 

A large part of {\textsc{qao}\xspace}'s power comes from the ability of quantum systems to tunnel through potential barriers.  In this article, we will focus on an $n$-qubit Hamiltonian, but by making it symmetric in the qubits, we can effectively reduce our problem to a one-dimensional tunneling problem.

This setup of one-dimensional tunneling in $n$ symmetric qubits has been studied by Farhi, Goldstone, and Gutmann \cite{Farhi2002} who considered tunneling through a thin spike of height $n$.  Reichardt \cite{Reichardt} showed that {\textsc{qao}\xspace} can tunnel through barriers with area $\Omega(\sqrt{n})$ in constant time.  Recently, Crosson and Deng \cite{Crosson} examined thin barriers of varying height, and Kong and Crosson \cite{Kong} found that sufficiently large barriers lead to exponential run-times.  We \cite{Brady} have numerically found the transitions between constant, polynomial, and exponential run-time scaling when the barrier height and width depend on the same power of $n$.

In this article, we shall focus on barriers of width proportional to $n^\alpha$ and height proportional to $n^\beta$ and will focus on barriers with $\alpha+\beta\geq 1/2$, which is above Reichardt's \cite{Reichardt} constant scaling region, and $2\alpha+\beta<1$ which is below Crosson ond Kong's \cite{Kong} exponential scaling region.  We will show that barriers in this intermediate size regime lead to polynomial scaling with {\textsc{qao}\xspace} scaling times of $\Omega\left((n^{\alpha+\beta-1/2})^2\right)$.


In section \ref{sec:ham}, we will present our problem and discuss the Hamiltonian governing the interactions of our $n$-qubit system.  Section \ref{sec:ana_gap} will present details of previous work on this problem and highlight the polynomial scaling region between $\alpha+\beta\geq1/2$ and $2\alpha+\beta<1$ where few solid results have been published.

Our problem lends itself to a large spin analysis using either spin coherent states or the Villain transformation.  Section \ref{sec:large_spin} will briefly touch on spin coherent states, which have been used to analyze this problem before \cite{Kong}, and will present an in depth analysis using the Villain transformation, resulting in a semi-classical Hamiltonian that describes our dynamics for large $n$.

Focusing on just the critical region of the problem where the spectral gap is smallest, section \ref{sec:quad_app} will provide and justify a toy model that approximates the semi-classical Hamiltonian in the large $n$ limit.  We will provide several arguments for why this model accurately represents the asymptotic behavior of our original problem.  Finally, in section \ref{sec:asymp}, we will use this model to derive an exact asymptotic expression for the scaling behavior of the spectral gap.








