\section{Previous Asymptotic Results}
\label{sec:ana_gap}
A folklore result by Goldstone \cite{Goldstone} says that for $\alpha<\beta$ and $\alpha<1/2$ the above defined minimum gap scales as a function of $n$ as

\begin{figure}
      \includegraphics[width=0.48\textwidth]{regions.eps}
      \caption{
           This graph shows how the scaling of the minimum gap ${g_\mathrm{min}}$ depends on the number $n$ of qubits and the size $n^\alpha\times n^\beta$ of the barrier that the Quantum Adiabatic Algorithm has to tunnel through. As described  in Eq.~\ref{eq:gold_pred} a folklore result by Goldstone predicts that for $\alpha<\beta$ there are three distinct regions where, as $n$ grows, the minimum gap ${g_\mathrm{min}}$ stays constant, decreases polynomially, or exponentially. In this article we prove that for $2\alpha+\beta<1$ and $\alpha+\beta>1/2$ we indeed have the polynomial scaling ${g_\mathrm{min}} \propto n^{1/2-\alpha-\beta}$. 
      }
      \label{fig:regions}
\end{figure}
While this result has never been published, its derivation is known to use ``large spin and instanton methods'' \cite{Goldstone}. 
Parts of this result have been verified by several other sources.

Reichardt \cite{Reichardt} has rigorously proven the existence of the constant region, and the $2\alpha+\beta=1$ transition boundary between exponential and polynomial gaps has recently been verified by Kong and Crosson \cite{Kong} using the instanton method \cite{Coleman} and numerically by us in a previous article \cite{Brady}.  The different scaling regions in $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:regions}.

The goal of the current article is to explore the polynomial region between $\alpha+\beta>1/2$ and $2\alpha+\beta<1$.  We will develop elementary techniques to analyze the spectral gap and will verify the $n^{1/2-\alpha-\beta}$ scaling behavior.

















\section{Large Spin  Approximation}
\label{sec:large_spin}

Our Hamiltonian readily lends itself to reinterpretation as the Hamiltonian for a particle with spin $J=n/2$.  A common analytic technique for dealing with a spin Hamiltonian is to use spin coherent states \cite{Auerbach} to create a semi-classical continuous version of the Hamiltonian.  Several groups \cite{Farhi2002, Kong} have used spin coherent states to analyze qubit systems, and Kong and Crosson \cite{Kong} have employed spin coherent states to analyze the symmetric barrier problem.  We will use a similar technique employing the Villain Transformation \cite{Villain} that has been used for similar problems \cite{Enz, Boulatov, Boxio}.

